# **Arcbeam Data Platform** 

## **About Arcbeam**

Arcbeam is an AI data platform that provides observability, monitoring, and quality control for LLM applications. It makes retrieval-augmented generation pipelines transparent by showing exactly which datasets are being used and how.

With Arcbeam, you can:

* Observe data at the ingestion layer and gain real-time visibility into source data usage down to the chunk level.  
* Monitor LLM observations by tracking queries, retrieved chunks, and responses across environments.   
* Enforce policies by applying compliance and governance rules to datasets with built-in or custom scoring. 

The platform integrates with vector databases like pgvector, and provides a web interface for visualization, management, and analysis.

## **Install**

### **Prerequisites**

* [Docker](https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/?utm_source=chatgpt.com) installed and running  
* Optional: Postgres database

### **System Resources** 

* At least 4 CPU cores and 16 GB RAM 

### **Open Ports**

* Make sure these ports aren’t already in use.  
  * 5432 (Postgres)  
  * 3000 (Arcbeam UI)

### **Setup** 

Create a file named docker-compose.yml and paste the following file contents. 

If you want to provide your own postgres database, ensure to update the DATABASE\_URL environment variable below:

| name: arcbeam-deployment services:   postgres:     image: postgres:17     environment:       POSTGRES\_DB: arcbeam       POSTGRES\_USER: postgres       POSTGRES\_PASSWORD: postgres     volumes:       \- postgres\_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data     ports:       \- "5432:5432"     healthcheck:       test: \["CMD-SHELL", "pg\_isready \-U postgres"\]       interval: 5s       timeout: 5s       retries: 5   web:     image: arcbeameng/arcbeam:betav0.0.5      ports:       \- "3000:3000"     environment:       DATABASE\_URL: postgresql://postgres:postgres@postgres:5432/arcbeam       BETTER\_AUTH\_SECRET: k+l+mAvW3IZgI3HIflO0XlGGv3QP2C321zG7YhQpavA= \# or run \`openssl rand \-base64 32       ORIGIN: http://localhost:3000       ARCBEAM\_SINGLE\_TENANT\_MODE: true       ARCBEAM\_DEFAULT\_EMAIL: [admin@arcbeam.ai](mailto:admin@arcbeam.ai)       ARCBEAM\_DEFAULT\_PASSWORD: admin            depends\_on:       postgres:         condition: service\_healthy volumes:   postgres\_data: |
| :---- |

Start the stack in the github repository: 

| docker compose up |
| :---- |

This will:

1. Start Postgres on port 5432\.  
2. Run migrations and seed data (one-off task)  
3. Launch the web app on [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000)

### **Stop the stack**

| docker compose down |
| :---- |

Data will persist in the **postgres\_data** volume across restarts.

## **Getting Started**

When you log in for the first time, you’ll see the onboarding page with setup instructions. Once you add your first data source, this screen will be replaced by the main Arcbeam homepage showing your projects, datasets, and observations.

![][image1]

Once your Arcbeam deployment is running, follow these steps to begin monitoring your AI applications.

### **Setting Up Your First Integration**

Integrations connect Arcbeam to your data sources so the platform can observe and track dataset usage. 

1. From the left sidebar, click Integrations.  
2. Select your preferred data source type.  
3. Enter the required connection details (connection string, collection name, schema mapping, etc).  
   1. The connection string must be in the format: postgresql://username:password@host:port/db  
   2. The Collection/Index Name is the table name of your embedding data  
   3. The data source column is the column or nested field that contains the raw document name  
   4. If any of the data are in nested fields, you can reference them using dot notation. Example: If your data sources are in a nested field in the metadata column called *source*, you can reference it as: metadata.source  
4. Click Save to verify the connection.

![][image2]

Once connected, datasets from that source will appear in the Datasets view.

### **Send Observations From Your Application**

#### Create API Key

To track how your applications are using data, you will need to generate an API key to authenticate to Arcbeam. 

1. Navigate to the settings page by clicking on the User icon on the top right of the screen.  
2. Click on the API Keys menu item on the left hand side.  
3. Generate an API key from the Create API Key button

![][image3]

#### Installation

To capture usage, your application can use our langchain connector to send data to the Arcbeam API whenever a query is processed. For more information visit [https://pypi.org/project/arcbeam-langchain-connector/](https://pypi.org/project/arcbeam-langchain-connector/).

| pip install arcbeam-langchain-connector |
| :---- |

#### Minimal Python Helper

| \# Basic LLM call with tracing from langchain\_openai import ChatOpenAI from langchain\_core.messages import HumanMessage from arcbeam\_langchain\_connector import ArcbeamHandler handler \= ArcbeamHandler( 	base\_url="YOUR\_ARCBEAM\_URL", api\_key=”YOUR\_ARCBEAM\_API\_KEY” ) llm \= ChatOpenAI(callbacks=\[handler\]) response \= llm.invoke(\[HumanMessage(content="What is the weather like today?")\]) print(response.content) \# For chains and agents, pass handler in config from langchain\_core.prompts import ChatPromptTemplate prompt \= ChatPromptTemplate.from\_template("Explain {topic} in two sentences.") chain \= prompt | llm result \= chain.invoke(     {"topic": "AI monitoring"},     config={"callbacks": \[handler\]} ) |
| :---- |

#### View Results in the UI

Return to the Projects page and select your project. You’ll see each query recorded along with the retrieved chunks, the model used and the input and output text.

![][image4]

### **Setting Up Projects To Observe Your Data**

When you first run Arcbeam, a default project is automatically created. You can connect your Postgres integration to this project right away, or create new projects to track specific LLM applications. Projects serve as the central place where you monitor application activity and apply policies to the data being used.

#### Locate Your Project ID

Open the Projects page in the UI and copy the ID from the Default Project card. You’ll use this ID in your application when sending usage events to Arcbeam.

### **Private Beta Known Issues**

During the private beta, you may notice some limitations in usage, integrations, and the user interface. These will be addressed in future releases.

* Usage  
  * Applications may experience increased latency. This is because data enrichment is performed inline rather than in the background.  
* Integrations  
  * Dataset Integrations cannot be edited once they are created.  
  * Unable to update integration details via the UI  
* User Interface  
* Dates that are not provided may display inconsistently, sometimes appearing as “Just Now” or “Unknown.”

## **FAQ**

Q: *Failed to save integration. Please try again.*

If you are getting this error, it is because the ORIGIN environment variable is most likely not set up correctly on the web service component. It should be set to the URL \+ port (if necessary) you see in the browser when using the platform.

Example: If you are accessing the platform on your browser through [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000), then ORIGIN should be set to [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000).

Example: If you are accessing the platform on your browser through [https://arcbeam.ai](https://arcbeam.ai) then ORIGIN should be set to https://arcbeam.ai

## **Closing And Support**

You are ready to observe your LLM applications, apply policies, and respond to alerts. Continue by iterating on policies, reviewing observations, and refining how your datasets are used.

If you have questions or need help, reach out to the Arcbeam team at eng@arcbeam.ai.
